=Kerry James Marshall: Along the Way |publisher=Camden Arts Centre |location=London |date=2005 |pages=27, 30\u201331 |chapter=Daylight |ISBN = 9781900470544 |oclc = 796082489}}\n* {{cite book |last=Tuymans |first=Luc |editor-last = |editor-first = |title=Signal. Exh. cat. [[Hamburger Bahnhof]] \u2013 Museum f\u00fcr Gegenwart, Berlin. |publisher=[[Staatliche Museen zu Berlin]] |location=Berlin |date=2001 |pages=2\u20133 |chapter=Der Fr\u00fchling kommt: Ideen, Fragen und Bemerkungen zum Konzept einer Ausstellung |ISBN = 9783886094493 |oclc = 313837829}}\n* {{cite book |last=Tuymans |first=Luc |editor-last=Celant |editor-first=Germano |title=Futoro presente passato/ Future Present Past. Exh. cat. Venice: Fondazione La Biennale di Venezia |publisher=Electa |location=Milan |date=1997 |pages=626 |chapter=The Broken Mirror |ISBN = 9788843561544 |oclc = 501499461}}\n* {{cite book |last=Tuymans |first=Luc |editor-last=Loock |editor-first=Ulrich |title=Luc Tuymans |publisher=Kunsthalle Bern |location=Bern |date=1992 |pages=11\u201336 |chapter=Disenchantment |ISBN = 9783857800795 |oclc = 881709830}}\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{refend}}\n{{commonscat}}\n{{Library resources box|by=yes|onlinebooks=no|wikititle=Luc Tuymans}}\n* {{Official website|www.luctuymans.com}} \n* [https://www.moma.org/artists/7520 Luc Tuymans], The Museum of Modern Art\n* [http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists/luc-tuymans-2612 Luc Tuymans], Tate Modern\n* [http://www.zeno-x.com/artists/LT/luc_tuymans.html Luc Tuymans], Zeno X Gallery\n* [https://www.davidzwirner.com/artists/luc-tuymans Luc Tuymans], David Zwirner Gallery\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuymans, Luc}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Contemporary painters]]\n[[Category:Belgian painters]]\n[[Category:Belgian contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:People from Antwerp]]\n[[Category:People from Mortsel]]\n[[Category:Royal Academy of Fine Arts (Antwerp) alumni]]\n[[Category:Order of Leopold]]\n[[Category:National pavilions]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Academy of Arts and Letters]]\n[[Category:Collection of the Los Angeles County Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Dallas Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:Collection of the Museum of Modern Art (New York City)]]\n[[Category:Carnegie Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Royal College of Art]]\n[[Category:Collection of the Tate galleries]]\n[[Category:Carnegie Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Dallas Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:Hammer Museum]]\n[[Category:Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]]\n[[Category:Collections of the Israel Museum]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Pinakothek der Moderne]]\n[[Category:Collection of the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian painters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Belgian painter}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Luc Tuymans\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = Luc_Tuymans_01.jpg\n| caption = Tuymans in 2009<br>\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1958|6|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Mortsel]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Belgian]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Carla Arocha]]|1999||end=}}\n| movement = \n| awards = {{flatlist|\n* ''Orders'':\n* [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]] ([[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Commander]])\n* ICOCEP-International Congress of Contemporary Painting (Medal of Honour)\n* ''Academies for Excellence'':\n* [[American Academy of Arts and Letters |American Academy of Arts and Letters (Honorary Member)]]\n* [[Academy of Arts  |Member of the Akademie der K\u00fcnste in Berlin]]\n* ''Academic Honours'':\n* [[University of Antwerp|University of Antwerp]] ([[Honorary Doctorate|Dr.h.c.]])\n* [[University of Fine Arts in Pozna\u0144|University of Arts Pozna\u0144]] ([[Honorary Doctorate|Dr.h.c.]])\n* [[Royal College of Art|Royal College of Art]] ([[Honorary Doctorate|Dr.h.c.]])<br>\n* ''Awards'':\n* [[The Vincent Award|The Vincent Award (Finalist)]] \n* Coutts Contemporary Art Foundation Awards\n* Flemish Culture Award for Visual Arts \n* ULTIMA Award\n* [[AmfAR, The Foundation for AIDS Research|AmfAR, The Foundation for AIDS Research Awards]]\n* ''Prizes'': \n* Cultuurprijs K.U. Leuven, Prijs Blanlin-Evrart \n }}\n| patrons = \n| field = {{flatlist|\n* [[Painting]]\n }}\n| training = {{flatlist|\n* [[LUCA School of Arts|Sint-Lukasinstituut Brussels]]\n* [[La Cambre|\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure des Arts visuels de La Cambre, Brussels]]\n* [[Royal Academy of Fine Arts (Antwerp)|Royal Academy of Fine Arts Antwerp]]\n* [[Free University Brussels|Free University of Brussels]]\n}}\n| works = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced = \n| website = {{url|https://www.luctuymans.com/|Official website}}<br>{{url|http://www.zeno-x.com/artists/LT/luc_tuymans.html|Zeno X Gallery}}<br> {{url|https://www.davidzwirner.com/artists/luc-tuymans|David Zwirner Gallery}}\n}}\n\n'''Luc Tuymans''' (born 14 June 1958) is a [[Belgian art|Belgian visual artist]] best known for his [[Painting|paintings]] which explore our relationship with history and confront our seeming ability to ignore it. [[World War II]] is a recurring theme in his work. He is a key figure of the generation of [[New European Painting|European figurative painters]] who gained renown at a time when many believed the medium had lost its relevance due to the [[Information Age|new digital age]]. \n\nMuch of Tuymans\u2019 work deals with moral complexity, specifically the coexistence of \u2018good\u2019 and \u2018evil\u2019.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Nina|first=Siegal|title=Luc Tuymans, Master of Moral Complexities, Tries Something New|journal=|date=21 March 2019 | publisher=The New York Times | location=New York |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/21/arts/design/luc-tuymans-palazzo-grassi-mosaic-la-pelle.html | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610015254/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/21/arts/design/luc-tuymans-palazzo-grassi-mosaic-la-pelle.html | archivedate=10 June 2019 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> His subjects range from major historical events such as [[the Holocaust]] to the seemingly inconsequential or banal: wallpaper, Christmas decorations or everyday objects for example. \n\nThe artist's sparsely-coloured [[Figurative painting|figurative paintings]] are made up of quick brush strokes of wet paint. Tuymans paints from [[Photographic image|photographic]] or [[Cinematography|cinematic]] images drawn from the media or [[public sphere]], as well as from his own [[Photograph|photographs]] and [[Drawing|drawings]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.davidzwirner.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/FINAL_LT_Press_Release.pdf | title=Luc Tuymans:  Forever, The Management of Magic | date=14 February \u2013 22 March 2008 | publisher=[[David Zwirner Gallery]] | location=New York | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301030757/http://www.davidzwirner.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/FINAL_LT_Press_Release.pdf | archivedate=1 March 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"roger travels\">{{cite book | last1 = Roger | first1 = White | title = The contemporaries travels in the 21st-century art world | publisher=Bloomsbury | series = | volume = 1 | edition = | location = New York | date = 2016 | page = 173 | isbn = 9781620400951 | OCLC = 1124364481}}</ref> They often appear intentionally [[out of focus]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.davidzwirner.com/exhibitions/226/ | title=Luc Tuymans: Corporate. 6 November\u201321 December 2010 | date = | publisher=[[David Zwirner Gallery]] | location=New York | url-status = | archiveurl = | archivedate = | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.davidzwirner.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/FINAL_LT_Press_Release.pdf | title=Luc Tuymans: Forever, The Management of Magic. 14 February\u201322 March 2008 | date = 29 January 2008 | publisher=[[David Zwirner Gallery]] | location=New York | url-status = | archiveurl = | archivedate = | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"roger travels\"/> The blurred effect is, however, created purposefully with painted strokes, it is not the result of a \u2018wiping away\u2019 technique.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/articles/Why-paintings-succeed-where-words-fail/19286 | title=Why paintings succeed where words fail | last = Harris | first = Gareth | date=9 September 2009 | publisher=The Art Newspaper | location=New York | url-status=dead | archiveurl = | archivedate = | df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nFormal and conceptual oppositions recur in his work, which is echoed in his remark that while \u2018sickness should appear in the way the painting is made\u2019 there is also pleasure in its making \u2013 a \u2018caressing\u2019 of the canvas. This reflects Tuymans\u2019 semantic shaping of the philosophical content of his work.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lindquist|first=Greg|title=Luc Tuymans|journal=The Brooklyn Rail|date=May 2010|url=http://brooklynrail.org/2010/05/artseen/luc-tuymans- | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222130519/https://brooklynrail.org/2010/05/artseen/luc-tuymans- | archivedate=22 February 2020 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Often allegorical, his titles add a further layer of imagery to his work \u2013 a layer that exists beyond the visible. The painting ''Gaskamer'' (''Gas Chamber'') exemplifies his use of titles to provoke associations in the mind of the viewer. Meaning, in his work, is never fixed; his paintings incite thought. A related characteristic of Tuymans' work is the way he often works in series, a method which enables one image to generate another through which images can be formulated and reformulated ad infinitum. Images are repeatedly analysed and distilled, and a large number of drawings, photocopies and [[Watercolor painting|watercolours]] are produced in preparation for his oil paintings.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://whitecube.com/exhibitions/exhibition/luc_tuymans_hoxton_square_2001 | title=Exhibitions - The Rumour, 5 September \u2014 13 October 2001 | date=1 March 2020 | publisher=White Cube | location=London | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301113132/https://whitecube.com/exhibitions/exhibition/luc_tuymans_hoxton_square_2001 | archivedate=1 March 2020 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Tate2004/> Each final painting is, however, completed in a single day.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Mullins | first1 = Charlotte | title = Painting People: Figure Painting Today | publisher=D.A.P./Distributed Art Publishers | series = | volume = | edition = | location = New York | date = 2008 | page = 150 | isbn = 9781933045832 | OCLC = 216938984}}</ref>  \n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Luc Tuymans Antichambre 1985 Collection M HKA - Collection of the Flemish Community.jpg|thumb|270px|<small>Luc Tuymans, ''Antichambre'', 1985<br>Oil on canvas, 69.9 \u00d7 80.1 cm, 271\u20442 \u00d7 319\u204416 inches, Collection [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Antwerp|M HKA Museum of Contemporary Art, Antwerp]] - Collection of the Flemish Community</small>|alt=]]\n[[File:Luc Tuymans Body 1990 Collection S.M.A.K. Stedelijk Museum voor Actuele Kunst, Ghent.jpg|thumb|270px|<small>Luc Tuymans, ''Body,'' 1990<br>Oil on canvas, 48.5 \u00d7 38.5 cm, 19 1\u20448 \u00d7 15 1\u20444 inches, Collection S.M.A.K. [[Stedelijk Museum voor Actuele Kunst]], Ghent</small>|alt=]]\n[[File:Luc Tuymans Der diagnostische Blick IV 1992 Private collection, on long-term loan to De Pont museum, Tilburg.jpg|thumb|270px|<small>Luc Tuymans, ''Der diagnostische Blick IV,'' 1992. Oil on canvas, 57 \u00d7 38.2 cm, 22 1\u20442 \u00d7 15 1\u20448 inches, Private collection, on long-term loan to [[De Pont Museum of Contemporary Art]], Tilburg</small>|alt=]]\n\nLuc Tuymans was born in [[Mortsel]] close to the city of [[Antwerp]] on 14 June 1958. His father was [[Flemish people|Belgian Flemish]] and his mother was [[Dutch people|Dutch]].<ref name=\"ilegems1\">{{in lang|nl}} {{cite book | last1 = Ilegems | first1 = Danny | title = Tuymans volgens Tuymans, Twintig jaar in gesprek met Luc Tuymans | publisher=Lebowski Publishers | series = | volume = 1 | edition = | location = Amsterdam | date = 2019 | page = 173 | isbn = 9789048849574 | OCLC = 1101667619}}</ref> During [[World War II]] his mother\u2019s family joined the [[Dutch resistance|Dutch Resistance]] and hid refugees, whereas some members of his father\u2019s family allegedly had sympathised with Nazi ideology.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.houstonpress.com/arts/luc-tuymans-nice-is-just-that-and-nothing-more-6599642 | title=Luc Tuymans: Nice. Is Just That and Nothing More | date=16 October 2013 | publisher=Houston Press. Voice Media Group | location=Houston | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224115825/https://www.houstonpress.com/arts/luc-tuymans-nice-is-just-that-and-nothing-more-6599642 | archivedate=24 February 2020 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Jackie | last=Wullschlager |   title=The Painterly Pessimist | url=https://www.ft.com/content/bb3eba30-3563-11e0-aa6c-00144feabdc0 | format=Fee required | publisher=Financial Times | date=12 February 2011 | accessdate=24 February 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://www.ft.com/content/bb3eba30-3563-11e0-aa6c-00144feabdc0 | archivedate=1 February 2020 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Karen | last=Wright |   title = In The Studio: Luc Tuymans, painter | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/in-the-studio-luc-tuymans-painter-8160324.html | format = | publisher=The Independent. London: Newspaper Publishing plc | date=22 September 2012 | accessdate=24 February 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219182941/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/in-the-studio-luc-tuymans-painter-8160324.html | archivedate=18 February 2018 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> This fact echoed through family conversations, raising moral questions and feelings of guilt, and the subject became a source of fascination and fear, later playing a key role in Tuymans\u2019 painting.<ref>{{cite news |first=Nina | last=Siegal |   title = Luc Tuymans, Master of Moral Complexities, Tries Something New | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/21/arts/design/luc-tuymans-palazzo-grassi-mosaic-la-pelle.html | format = | publisher=New York: The New York Times Company | date=21 March 2019 | accessdate=24 February 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610015254/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/21/arts/design/luc-tuymans-palazzo-grassi-mosaic-la-pelle.html | archivedate=10 June 2019 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nHis interest in art manifested itself at a young age, and his ability was first recognised during a summer holiday in [[Zundert]], when he won a drawing competition. He later said this event gave him a sense of the path he had to take. When he was eight or nine, his uncle took him to the [[Gemeentemuseum]] in [[The Hague]] where he saw a painting by [[Mondrian]]. In a much later conversation, he explained how \u2018looking at that abstract painting was my first art experience.... I felt the magic of art in it.... I did understand the monumentality of that work.\u2019<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite news | last = Van Puymbroeck | first = Rik | url = https://www.tijd.be/sabato/kunst/luc-tuymans-de-achterlijkheid-in-onze-maatschappij-groeit-met-de-seconde-ondanks-de-technische-vooruitgang/10107773.html | accessdate = | date =   | work = De Tijd | title = Luc Tuymans: 'De achterlijkheid in onze maatschappij groeit met de seconde, ondanks de technische vooruitgang'| archive-url  = | archive-date = | url-status = | df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n==Work (paintings)==\n===Early work, 1972\u201394===\nDuring the crucial first phase of Tuymans\u2019 artistic development, his painting method evolved rapidly, and his first solo and group [[Exhibition|exhibitions]] took place. According to the [[catalogue raisonn\u00e9]],<ref name=Volume12018>{{cite book |last=Meyer-Hermann |first=Eva |title=Luc Tuymans: Catalogue Raisonn\u00e9 of the Paintings, 1972\u20131994 (Volume 1)|date=2018 |publisher= New York: David Zwirner Books; New Haven: Yale University Press}}</ref> he created nearly 200 paintings on canvas or hardboard during this period. His first known painting dates from 1972 and the first public exhibited painting was created in 1977, entitled ''Self-Portrait''. He was a student at the time, and submitted it to the national painting competition in Belgium, which he won.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/22613/lot/33/ | title = My Bonhams | date = | publisher = www.bonhams.com. Bonhams | location = | accessdate=10 March 2020|url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217073544/http://www.bonhams.com/auctions/22613/lot/33/ | archivedate=17 February 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1979\u20131980, Tuymans worked in collaboration with Marc Schepers on two local projects entitled ''Morguen''. The artists asked families from a neighbourhood in Antwerp for historical family photographs, a collection they built on with their own documentation of the area. The following year, they published the project in the ''Tijdschrift voor levende Volkskunst'' (''Journal of Living Folk Art''), as a journal modelled on the historical ''Volksfoto'' magazine. Six months later they organized a second photo project. This time, they focused on the workers\u2019 district surrounding [[St. Andrew's Church, Antwerp]].<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite news |first1 = Koen | last1 = Brams |first2 = Dirk | last2 = P\u00fcltau |title = Actuele volkskunst: Interview met Marc Schepers |page=1\u20134 | url = https://www.dewitteraaf.be/artikel/detail/nl/3875 | format = | publisher = Brussels: De Witte Raaf | date = August 2012 | accessdate=12 March 2020 |url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224145842/https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/07/arts/design/07tuymans.html%20Putting%20the%20Wrongs%20of%20History%20in%20Paint | archivedate=11 October 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBetween 1980 and 1985, Tuymans stopped painting, dedicating himself to [[Experimental film|experimentation with film]]. Among other film-projects, he created ''Feu d\u2019artifice'' (''Firework'')<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Tuymans | first1 = Luc|title = Luc Tuymans: Dusk/Penumbra | publisher = Museu Serralves =|article = Facsimile of six pages relating to Feu d\u2019artifice and Het leven op aarde from Luc Tuymans\u2019 1981 journal |volume = 1 |edition = |location = Porto |date = 2006|page = |isbn = 9789727391646\n | OCLC = 938742300}}</ref> and made plans for an unrealized, [[Semidocumentary|semi-documentary]] [[feature film]]. Some of the film fragments he made later served as inspiration for paintings.<ref>{{cite book|first = Bill | last = Horrigan |title = Luc Tuymans|article =  Cinema, Belgium, Tuymans: A Note |url = | format = | page=59\u201365 | publisher = ed. Madeleine Grynsztejn and Helen Molesworth. San Francisco: San Francisco Museum of Modern Art | date = 2009 | accessdate=}}</ref> When Tuymans resumed painting in 1985, he changed his technique, and since then he never spent more than a day working on a painting.<ref>{{cite magazine |first = Marina | last = Cashdan |title = Interview with Luc Tuymans |url = | format = | page=22\u201342 | publisher = The White Review 7 | date = | accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1978 on, Tuymans' paintings centred on European memories of [[World War II]], confronting [[Adorno]]'s famous question whether art was impossible following [[The Holocaust|the holocaust]], and \u2018the collapse of any coherent tradition in painting\u2019 described by [[Peter Schjeldahl]].<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Schjeldahl | first1 = Peter|title = Hot, Cold, Heavy, Light, 100 Art Writings 1988\u20132018|publisher = Abrams Press. www.abramsbooks.com|article = Facsimile of six pages relating to Feu d\u2019artifice and Het leven op aarde from Luc Tuymans\u2019 1981 journal |volume = 1 |edition = |location =New York |date = 2019}}</ref> One of his works from this period is a small painting of the gas chamber in [[Dachau]], entitled ''Gaskamer'' ([[Gas chambers of Treblinka|''Gas Chamber'']]), 1986. This painting was based on a watercolour he had done on site.<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite web | url=https://www.groene.nl/artikel/albert-speer-op-ski-s | title=K. Kleijn, Albert Speer op ski's | date=23 March 2011 | publisher=De Groene Amsterdammer | location = Amsterdam | accessdate=12 March 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312225852/https://www.groene.nl/artikel/albert-speer-op-ski-s | archivedate=12 March 2020 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> As [[J.S. Marcus]] from ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote, the painting \u2018simplified the means of painting.... flattened the perspective, muted the colour and the direction of the composition.... To save the painting he almost makes it disappear.\u2019<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124654830763786455 | title=J. S. Marcus, Luc Tuymans Captures the Moment (3 July 2009) | date = | publisher=Wall Street Journal | location = New York | accessdate=25 February 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222130508/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124654830763786455 | archivedate=22 February 2020 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>  Other paintings that date from this period are the 1988 four-part painting ''Die Zeit'' (''The Time'') in which Tuymans combines a portrait of the &nbsp;[[Reinhard Heydrich|Nazi frontman Reinhard Heydrich]] with two spinach tablets and a [[cityscape]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ensembles.mhka.be/items/4114 | title=Luc Tuymans, Die Zeit | date = | publisher=M HKA Museum of Contemporary Art Antwerp | location = Antwerp | accessdate=12 March 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301233644/http://ensembles.mhka.be/items/4114 | archivedate=1 March 2020 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the 1989 painting [[Wiedergutmachung|''Die Wiedergutmachung'']] (''The Reparation'') that depicts the eyes of [[Nazi human experimentation|gypsy children who had been experimented on by the Nazis]].<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite web | url=https://www.demorgen.be/nieuws/luc-tuymans-the-horror~bd223d92/\n | title=Bernard Dewulf, Luc Tuymans: the horror. 'Mooi is voor mij een scheldwoord', 8 juni 2002 | date = | publisher=De Morgen | location = Ghent | accessdate=12 March 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302031531/https://www.demorgen.be/nieuws/luc-tuymans-the-horror~bd223d92/ | archivedate=2 March 2020 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFrom the late 1970s, Tuymans also began to paint portraits of himself and imaginary portraits, anonymous individuals, and historical and public figures. Superficially, most of these images seem to be [[Portrait|traditional portraits]]; the approach is dispassionate and not psychological. His portraits strip individuality away, leaving the body resembling a shell, the face a mask.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.e-flux.com/announcements/32160/luc-tuymans/ | title=Luc Tuymans | date = | publisher=E-flux | location = New York | accessdate=12 March 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929174742/http://www.e-flux.com/announcements/32160/luc-tuymans/ | archivedate=29 September 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Another example of his figurative portrait work is ''Der diagnostische Blick'' (''The Diagnostic Look''), a series of ten paintings from 1992 based on clinical images of bodies and body parts he found in a physician's manual on physical diseases.<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite web | url=https://www.volkskrant.nl/nieuws-achtergrond/ongrijpbaar-als-kringen-in-een-waterplas-de-smoezelige-schilderijtjes-van-luc-tuymans~bc857d26/ | title=Paul Depondt, Ongrijpbaar als kringen in een waterplas de smoezelige schilderijtjes van Luc Tuymans~bc857d26 | date = | publisher=De Volkskrant | location = Amsterdam | accessdate=12 March 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217044424/https://myprivacy.dpgmedia.net/?siteKey=PUBX2BuuZfEPJ6vF&callbackUrl=https://www.volkskrant.nl/privacy-wall/accept?redirectUri=%2fnieuws-achtergrond%2fongrijpbaar-als-kringen-in-een-waterplas-de-smoezelige-schilderijtjes-van-luc-tuymans%7ebc857d26%2f | archivedate=17 February 2020 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs Meyer-Hermann wrote in the [[catalogue raisonn\u00e9]], the artist first elucidated his [[theoretical approach]] in an unrealized proposal for a group exhibition, entitled ''Virus of the Vanities''. Here, he defines key terms and develops a dialectic between the \u2018virus\u2019 as representative of the \u2018cult\u2019, and \u2018vanity\u2019 as a projection of \u2018culture\u2019, also opposing the \u2018anecdotal\u2019 (as in the portrait or still life) to the \u2018symbolic\u2019 (as in representations of time or death). Tuymans refers to nine of his paintings dating from 1978 to 1990 to support his ideas.<ref name=Volume12018/>\n\nTuymans\u2019 first exhibition in North America, entitled ''Superstition'', was held in 1994 at the [[David Zwirner Gallery]] (it was also shown later at the Art Gallery of [[York University]] in Toronto, [[Renaissance Society|The Renaissance Society]] at the University of Chicago, and London\u2019s [[Institute of Contemporary Arts|ICA Institute of Contemporary Arts]]). The exhibition reflected humankind\u2019s scepticism and spiritual indifference as manifested by our attitude to recent historical events.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://renaissancesociety.org/exhibitions/394/luc-tuymans-superstition/ | title=Luc Tuymans: Superstition: Exhibitions: The Renaissance Society. Luc Tuymans: Superstition: Exhibitions | date = 1995 | publisher=The Renaissance Society, renaissancesociety.org | location = Chicago | accessdate=17 March 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023013140/http://renaissancesociety.org/exhibitions/394/luc-tuymans-superstition/ | archivedate = 23 October 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===1995\u20132006===\n[[File:Luc Tuymans Lumumba 2000 The Museum of Modern Art, New York. Fractional and promised gift of Donald L. Bryant, Jr.jpg|thumb|270px|<small>Luc Tuymans, ''Lumumba'', 2000, oil on canvas, 62 \u00d7 46 cm, 24 3\u20448 \u00d7 18 1\u20448 inches,  Collection [[Museum of Modern Art|The Museum of Modern Art]], New York</small>|alt=]]\nSince 1995 Tuymans' international renown grew, and he participated in over 140 group exhibitions and had 47 solo shows in Europe, North America, and Asia. Between these dates, he created 198 works he classified as paintings, several murals and textile wall hangings.<ref name=Volume22018>Meyer-Hermann, Eva. ''Luc Tuymans: Catalogue Raisonn\u00e9 of the Paintings, 1995\u20132006'', Volume 2, New York: David Zwirner Books; New Haven: Yale University Press, 2018, pp. 6, 424\u2013451</ref> \n \nHis exhibition ''Heimat'', held in 1995 at the [[Zeno X]] Gallery in Antwerp and the Mus\u00e9e des Beaux Arts in Nantes, was a response to political events in Flanders and targeted [[Flemish Movement|Flemish nationalism]]. Pieces shown were all dated from that year and included ''The Flag'', ''A Flemish Village'', the Flemish memorial ''Ijzertoren'' ([[Yser Tower|''Yser Tower'']]), a portrait of the Flemish writer [[Ernest Claes]] entitled ''A Flemish Intellectual'', and ''Home Sweet Home''. Several of the paintings included in ''Heimat'' were shown the following year (1996\u201397) in the exhibition ''Face \u00e0 l\u2018histoire'' held at the [[Centre Pompidou|Centre Georges Pompidou]] in Paris, which looked at modern artists\u2019 responses to major historical and political events over the preceding sixty years.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} {{cite web | url=https://www.centrepompidou.fr/media/document/e9/59/e9595d6097fd4010b2195bbd0e8cd04a/normal.pdf | title=Face \u00e0 l'Histoire 1933-1996, engagement, t\u00e9moignage, vision | date=1996 | publisher=Centre Georges Pompidou | location=Paris | accessdate=16 March 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180801221242/https://www.centrepompidou.fr/media/document/e9/59/e9595d6097fd4010b2195bbd0e8cd04a/normal.pdf | archivedate=1 August 2018 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In a later 2014 interview discussing the ''Heimat'' series with ''De Witte Raaf'' he expressed his particular dislike of the separatist, far-right Flemish political party the [[Vlaams Blok]] (Flemish block), which achieved its best electoral result to date in Antwerp in 1994, stating: \u2018I was ashamed that I was from Antwerp!\u2019<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite journal | last1 = Brams | first1 = Koen | last2 = P\u00fcltau | first2 = Dirk | title = Ik huiver van een identiteitsdiscours als het over cultuur gaat\u2019 Gesprek met Luc Tuymans over Belgische kunst en Vlaams-nationalisme | location = Brussel | journal = De Witte Raaf | year = 2014 | volume = | issue = 169 mei-juni | pages = |url = https://www.dewitteraaf.be/artikel/detail/nl/3994| accessdate = 20 March 2020|url-status =  | archiveurl = | archivedate = }}</ref> \n\nIn 1996, Tuymans\u2019 exhibition ''Heritage'', held at the [[David Zwirner Gallery]], consisted of ten new paintings of the same title, all inspired by the mood that prevailed in the U.S. following the [[Oklahoma City bombing]]. The series depicts normal, almost stereotypical American imagery: a painting of two baseball caps (''Heritage I''); [[Mount Rushmore]] (''Heritage VII''); a man working (''Heritage VIII''); a portrait and a birthday cake (''Heritage IX''). The series also includes a portrait of the wealthy [[Ku Klux Klan]] member Joseph Milteer (''Heritage VI'').<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.davidzwirner.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/PR96.pdf | title=Luc Tuymans: The Heritage | date=20 September \u2013 19 October 1996 | publisher=[[David Zwirner Gallery]] | location=New York | accessdate=26 June 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923213007/http://www.davidzwirner.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/PR96.pdf | archivedate=23 September 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nIn 2000, Tuymans attracted attention with his series of political paintings ''Mwana Kitoko'' (''Beautiful Boy''), inspired by [[Baudouin of Belgium|King Baudouin]] of Belgium\u2019s state visit to the [[Congo]] in the 1950s. These works were exhibited in 2000 at the [[David Zwirner Gallery]] and the following year in the Belgian Pavilion at the [[Venice Biennale]].\n\nAt [[Documenta 11]] in 2002, which focused on works of art containing political or social commentary, many expected Tuymans to present new work created in response to the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 attacks on New York]]. Instead, he presented a simple [[Still life|still-life]] executed on a massive scale, deliberately ignoring all reference to world events.<ref>{{cite web | last = |first = | authorlink   = | year = 2004 | url = http://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-modern/exhibition/luc-tuymans/luc-tuymans-room-7 | publisher = [[Tate Modern]], London | title = Luc Tuymans, 23 June \u2013 26 September 2004 | accessdate = | archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20200222130520/https://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-modern/exhibition/luc-tuymans/luc-tuymans-room-7 | archive-date = 22 Feb 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> This inevitably led to some negative criticism.<ref>{{in lang|de}} {{cite news | last = Seyfarth | first = Ludwig | url =  \nhttp://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/documenta-enttaeuschung-rueckkehr-zur-tradition-luc-tuymans-beitrag-zur-d11-161812.html | accessdate = 20  March 2020 | date = 20 June 2002 | publisher = Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung | work =  | title = R\u00fcckkehr zur Tradition - Luc Tuymans' Beitrag zur D11. Luc Tuymans gilt als einer der herausragendsten Maler der Gegenwart in Europa. Auf der d11 entt\u00e4uscht seine Kunst. | archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304213721/http://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/documenta-enttaeuschung-rueckkehr-zur-tradition-luc-tuymans-beitrag-zur-d11-161812.html | archive-date = 4 March 2016 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tuymans however, described his decision as a deliberate strategy of \u2018sublimation\u2019: \u2018In ''Still-Life'' the idea of banality becomes larger than life, it is taken to an impossible extreme. It\u2019s actually just an icon, an almost purely cerebral painting, more like a light projection. The attacks [[September 11 attacks|[9/11]]] were also an assault on aesthetics. That gave me the idea of reacting with a sort of anti-picture, with an idyll, albeit an inherently twisted one.\u2019<ref name=\"Tate2004\" />\n\nIn 2004 Tate Modern in London and in 2006 Museu Serralves in Porto devoted major solo exhibitions to Tuymans work.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\n===From 2007 onwards===\n[[File:Luc Tuymans The Shore 2014 Tate. Presented by the artist and David Zwirner, 2016.jpg|thumb|270px|<small>Luc Tuymans, ''The Shore'', 2014<br>Oil on canvas, 194.2 \u00d7 353.7 cm, 761\u20442 \u00d7 1391\u20444 inches, Collection [[Tate Modern]], London.<br>Presented by the artist and David Zwirner, 2016</small>|alt=]]\n\nSince 2007, Tuymans participated in over 200 group exhibitions and had over 30 solo shows in [[Europe]], [[North America]], and [[Asia]]. During this period (2007\u201319) he produced 180 works he classified as paintings, plus several [[Mural|murals]] and [[Textile arts|textile wall hangings]].<ref name=Volume32018>Meyer-Hermann, Eva. ''Luc Tuymans: Catalogue Raisonn\u00e9 of the Paintings, 2007\u20132018'', Volume 3, New York: David Zwirner Books; New Haven: Yale University Press, 2018, pp. 6, 380-425</ref>\n\nHis 2007 exhibition ''Les Revenants'' at [[Zeno X]] focused on the social influence of the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] in education. In 2007, a major [[Retrospective exhibition|retrospective]] was organized by the [[Hall of Art, Budapest|M\u0171csarnok Kunsthalle]] in [[Budapest]] (2007-2008) which travelled as ''Luc Tuymans: Wenn der Fr\u00fchling kommt'' to [[Haus der Kunst]] in [[Munich]] in 2008 and as ''Come and See'' to the [[Zach\u0119ta|Zach\u0119ta National Gallery of Art in Warsaw]]. Each venue had a different set of paintings on show. His 2008 solo show at [[David Zwirner Gallery]], entitled ''The Management of Magic'', explored the \u2018Disney-fication\u2019 of consumer society. From 2009 to 2011, this major exhibition travelled to four cities in [[North America]]: the [[Wexner Center for the Arts]], the [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art|SFMOMA San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]], [[Dallas Museum of Art|DMA Dallas Museum of Art]], and the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago|MCA Museum of Contemporary Art in Chicago]]. It then moved to its final stop in Belgium at [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels|BOZAR \u2013 Palais des Beaux-Arts in Brussels]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Barbareschi | first = Beatrice | authorlink = | year = 21 February 2008 | url = http://contemporaryartnewyork.blogspot.com/2008/02/david-zwirner-luc-tuymans-forever.html | publisher = Contemporary Art New York | title = David Zwirner: \u201cLuc Tuymans: Forever, The Management of Magic.\u201d | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = | archivedate = | url-status = | df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nBetween 2006 and 2008, solo exhibitions devoted to Tuymans were held in diverse locations: at M\u0171csarnok Kunsthalle in Budapest in 2007\u201308; at Zach\u0119ta National Gallery of Art in Warsaw and at Haus der Kunst in Munich in 2008.\n\nIn 2012, Tuymans was invited by the Polish artist [[Miros\u0142aw Ba\u0142ka]] to take part in a project in the town where [[Miros\u0142aw Ba\u0142ka|Ba\u0142ka]] had grown up: [[Otwock]]. This project involved interpreting the town\u2019s history through artworks which were spread across over twenty locations. Tuymans contributed the painting ''Die Nacht'' (2012), which refers to [[Hans-J\u00fcrgen Syberberg]]\u2019s epic 1985 film installation on [[German history]]. During the second season in 2012, this painting hung in Ba\u0142ka\u2019s childhood bedroom. Tuymans also installed hundreds of black balloons in the ruins of Zofi\u00f3wka, a former hospital for people with mental health conditions. In 1940, the building was part of the Otwock ghetto, and in 1942, during the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u20131945)|Nazi occupation of Poland]], its inhabitants either died of starvation, were shot, or were sent to the [[Treblinka extermination camp|Treblinka concentration camp]].<ref>afterall.org, 8 May 2014.</ref> \n\nAt the retrospective exhibition entitled ''Intolerance'' staged by [[Qatar Museums Authority|QM Gallery Al Riwaq]] in Doha in 2016, Tuymans presented a new body of work entitled ''The Arena I\u2013VI''. These works depict violence in 1942. \u2018With visual similarities to Francisco Goya\u2019s ''The Third of May 1808'', 1814, Tuymans\u2019 strong highlighting of central figures encased by a blackened, scruffy vignette suggests a diaspora, revolution, or an uneasy static mob. There is a sense of pent-up aggression that lies beneath the surface of the ethnically ambiguous and androgynous forms.\u2019<ref> https://www.artforum.com/picks/qatar-museums-gallery-alriwaq-56656</ref>\n\n'''Copyright infringement'''\n\nIn January 2015 Tuymans was found guilty of plagiarism by a Belgian civil court after he used a photograph taken by Katrijn Van Giel as the source of his painting ''A Belgian Politician'' (2011),<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite news | last = Bergmans | first = Eline | url =https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20150120_01484091 | url-access = | date = 20 January 2015 | work = De Standaard | title = Tuymans veroordeeld voor plagiaat | archive-url  = | archive-date = | url-status = | df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Artsy Editors | first =  | authorlink =  | title = This Year\u2019s Biggest Art News Stories | location = New York | journal = Artsy | year = 15 December 2015 | url =https://www.artsy.net/article/artsy-editorial-the-biggest-art-news-stories | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200222130507/https://www.artsy.net/article/artsy-editorial-the-biggest-art-news-stories | archive-date = 22 February 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> a portrait of [[Jean-Marie Dedecker]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://hyperallergic.com/176138/luc-tuymans-convicted-of-plagiarism-for-painting-photo-of-politician/|title=Luc Tuymans Found Guilty of Plagiarism for Painting Photo of Politician|date=2015-01-20|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-16}}</ref> Tuymans [[Appeal|appealed against the ruling]], claiming that the painting was a [[parody]] \u2013 a critique of Belgian conservatism.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> He and Van Giel reached an amicable, confidential out-of-court settlement in October 2015. The British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' supported the artist in this dispute, commenting on the way Tuymans never makes [[Photorealism|photorealistic representation]]s of original photos, and describing how \u2018his work bears witness to a career-long survey of all images.<ref>{{cite news | last = Adrian | first = Searle | url = http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/jan/21/luc-tuysmans-katrijn-van-giel-dedecker-legal-case?cmp=share_btn_fb | url-access = | date = 21 January 2015 | work = The Guardian | title = Why Belgium's plagiarism verdict on Luc Tuymans is beyond parody | archive-url  =  | archive-date =  | url-status = | df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Other works==\n===Works on paper===\n[[Drawing]] has been integral to Tuymans\u2019 artistic practice from the start. Sketches, [[Watercolor painting|watercolours]] and other small-scale works form the bedrock of his work for they constitute, for him, a way of thinking through an idea. Important features of Tuymans' artistic approach can be found in these preparatory pieces such as his voluntary choice of low-quality materials and his incorporation of found elements. Such works are both visual preparations for later paintings and exteriorisations of thought processes. As Tuymans said in an interview with Josef Helfenstein in 1997: \u2018drawing is particularly important because I become mentally involved in the work and the picture. What is important for me is the idea of thinking while I draw, particularly in the tiny drawings. It helps to have everything under control\u2019.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Tuymans | first1 =Luc|last2 =Helfenstein| first2 =Josef||last3 =Reust| first3 =Hans Rudolf|last4 =Rinder| first4 =Lawrence|author-link =|title =Luc Tuymans: Premonition, Zeichnungen/Drawings [Published on the occasion of an exhibition organized by Kunsthalle Bern, Bern, April 23\u2013June 29, 1997, Berkeley Art Museum, Oktober 10\u2013December 31, 1997; Capc Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain, Bordeaux, January 30\u2013April 11, 1998]|publisher =Benteli |series =|volume = | edition =| location =Wabern-Bern, Germany|date = 1997|page= 9 and 35 |isbn =9783716510698|OCLC = 884075562}}</ref> Elsewhere in the interview, Tuymans explained that he mostly draws from memory and that he finds it better not to start drawing immediately when he sees something, but that he draws \u2018on the basis of a fragmentary memory.\u2019 This is elaborated on later in the 1997 interview with Helfenstein, when he describes how he usually prefers to draw after seeing something, \u2018on the basis of a fragmentary memory\u2019. Each drawing is more than a visual record: it forms part of a wider reflective process. The first comprehensive exhibition of Tuymans' drawings and other works on paper from the years 1975\u201396 was on view in an exhibition that travelled to [[Kunsthalle Bern]], Bern; [[Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive|Berkeley Art Museum]], Berkeley; and [[CAPC mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Bordeaux|Capc Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain]], Bordeaux (in 1997\u201398).\n\n===Murals ===\n{{See also|List of Murals by Luc Tuymans}}\n[[File:Luc_tuymans33424762.ogg|thumb|thumbtime=1:00thumbtime=2:09|right|270px|Luc Tuymans talks about his triptych mural <br>''St. Croce'', 2010, MCA Museum of Contemporary Art in Chicago.]]\n\nTuymans has made about 50 site-specific murals since the mid-1990s, five permanent and the rest temporary. Unlike the permanent mural paintings, Tuymans other mural paintings are temporary events and installations created for exhibitions. The type of mural techniques used is either acrylic paint or fresco applied directly on the existing wall surfaces. On rare occasions, he also made textile murals, which are based on drawings that are scanned and mechanically produced. As he said in a video interview he gave about the triptych mural painting ''S. Croce'' (2010), they are always related to the 'raw space' and 'it is the element of approach which is important with murals', he also mentioned that 'If I work on a wall I feel much more free than on a canvas.' \n\nThe first permanent mural was created in 1995 in Antwerp at Caf\u00e9 Alberto. It features a larger version of the painting ''Superstition''.<ref name=Volume22018>Meyer-Hermann, Eva. ''Luc Tuymans: Catalogue Raisonn\u00e9 of the Paintings, 1972\u20131994'', Volume 1, New York: David Zwirner Books; New Haven: Yale University Press, 2018, pp. 5, 425, 426</ref> In 2007 Tuymans executed a permanent mural based on ''Bloodstains'' (1993) on the ceiling of the ballroom of the former Ringtheater. This same year, the building was taken over by Troubleyn/Laboratorium, the performance company run by the Belgian playwright and artist [[Jan Fabre]].<ref>Gerrit Vermeiren, ed., Luc Tuymans: I Don\u2019t Get It, 125\u201327. Exh. cat. MuHKA Museum van Hedendaagse Kunst Antwerpen, Antwerp. Ghent: Ludion, 2007</ref><ref>Sigrid Bousset, Katrien Bruyneel, and Mark Geurden, ed., Troubleyn/Laboratorium: Jan Fabre. Brussels: Mercatorfonds, 2016.</ref name=Volume22018>Meyer-Hermann, Eva. ''Luc Tuymans: Catalogue Raisonn\u00e9 of the Paintings, 1972\u20131994'', Volume 2, New York: David Zwirner Books; New Haven: Yale University Press, 2018, pp. 5, 384-85</ref> In February 2012, Tuymans used the motif of ''Angel'' for a permanent mural created in the second balcony foyer of the Concertgebouw Brugge. Tuymans gave the [[Staatsschauspiel Dresden]] two permanent murals created for the main staircases of the building on Theaterstrasse in 2013. These two murals are based on the paintings ''Peaches'' (2012) and ''Technicolor'' (2012).<ref>Lynne Cooke and Tommy Simoens, ed., Luc Tuymans: Intolerance, 30; ill. 31. Exh. cat. QM Gallery Al Riwaq, Qatar Museums, Doha. Antwerp: Ludion, 2015</ref><ref name=Volume32018/>''Arena'' (2017) is the most recent permanent mural created for the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Ghent|Museum of Fine Arts in Ghent]]. This work is a fresco mural that consists of three panels located at the end of a curved gallery in the museum\u2019s hall.\n\n===Mosaics===\n[[File:Luc Tuymans - Dead Skull - square in front of Museum aan de Stroom Antwerpen 02.jpg|thumb|270px|right|<small>Luc Tuymans, ''Dead Skull'', 2010<br>[[Museum aan de Stroom |MAS Museum aan de Stroom]], Antwerp</small>]]\n\nThe first [[mosaic]] Tuymans made was ''Dead Skull'', 2010, commissioned by the [[Museum aan de Stroom|MAS Museum aan de Stroom (Museum by the River)]] as a permanent installation in the museum square on the Hanzestedenplaats in Antwerp. It is a 40 m<sup>2</sup> stone mosaic that evokes Tuymans\u2019 painting of the same name created in 2002, which in turn refers to a memorial plaque dedicated to the 16th-century painter [[Quinten Metsys]] from Antwerp which can be found on the facade of the [[Cathedral of Our Lady (Antwerp)|Cathedral of Our Lady]] in Antwerp.<ref name=Volume32018/> The painting was first transformed into a grid pattern of 488 by 488 pixels. Using that image and a specially designed [[Digital conversion|digital conversion technique]], a mosaic was created from 96,569 stones of 11 different colours.<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite news | last = Erik | first = Raspoet | url = https://www.demorgen.be/nieuws/de-schedel-van-luc-tuymans~bca8ae9e/ | accessdate  = 24 March 2020 | date = 18 May 2010 | work = New York Times Literary Supplement | title = De schedel van Luc Tuymans | archive-url = | archive-date = | url-status = | df=dmy-all}}</ref> The installation began in the winter of 2009 and was finished in the summer of 2010. ''Dead Skull'' is hardly distinguishable as an image when you are on the ground floor, but the higher you climb in the [[Museum aan de Stroom|MAS]], the more clearly the skull becomes visible.<ref>{{cite web | last =  | first = | authorlink = | year = | url = https://www.mas.be/en/page/museum-square-%E2%80%98dead-skull%E2%80%99 | publisher = MAS Museum aan de Stroom, Antwerpen | title = Museum square with \u2018Dead Skull\u2019 | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171206062334/https://www.mas.be/en/page/museum-square-%E2%80%98dead-skull%E2%80%99 | archivedate = 6 December 2017 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nThe second mosaic Tuymans made was ''Schwarzheide'', made at the time of his exhibition ''La Pelle'' at [[Palazzo Grassi]] in 2019. This work was produced by Fantini Mosaici in Milan and is based on Tuymans\u2019 eponymous oil on canvas dated 1989 representing a German forced-labour camp. The full image could only be seen from the balustrades, overlooking the atrium of [[Palazzo Grassi]]. Due to the floods that hit Venice in February 2020, the site-specific mosaic was dismantled.<ref>{{cite web | last =  | first =  | authorlink =  | year = 2019 | url = https://www.palazzograssi.it/en/events/all/dismantling-of-luc-tuymans-mosaic/ | publisher =  | title = Dismantling of Luc Tuymans' Mosaic | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200325161104/https://www.palazzograssi.it/en/events/all/dismantling-of-luc-tuymans-mosaic/ | archivedate = 25 March 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Graphic works===\nTuymans experimented with [[printmaking]] from the late 1980s on, producing a graphic oeuvre of about 90 works, which focus \u2013 like his paintings \u2013 on the mediation and translation of images in the [[mass media]]. He has explored various printing methods such as [[Photocopying|photocopy]], [[Inkjet printing|inkjet]], [[Offset printing|offset]], [[Monotyping|monotype]], [[Screen printing|screen-printing]], [[lithography]], [[etching]], and silver gelatine prints, using unusual supports such as wallpaper, security glass and PVC.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Sellink | first1 = Manfred|author-link = |title = Luc Tuymans Graphic Works 1989\u20142012 | publisher = Ludion|series =|volume = 1 |edition = |location = Antwerp|date = 2012|page =7\u20149|isbn = 9461300514 | OCLC = 856579856}}</ref> In a similar way to his paintings, his printed images often appear blurred or reduced. They are frequently based on photographs or film stills, which the artist photographs and re-photographs until much of the original detail is lost.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists/luc-tuymans-2612 | last = Parkin | first = Michela | date = June 1997 | title=Luc Tuymans born 1958 | publisher = Tate | location=London|accessdate=12 March 2020|url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321135900/https://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists/luc-tuymans-2612 | archivedate=21 March 2019 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The four-colour etching ''Isabel, Diorama, Scramble, Twenty Seventeen'' (2017) for example, is based on iPhone photographs Tuymans took while painting. These images reveal an early, unfinished stage of the work. The paint strokes Tuymans placed in the margin of the painting and at the edges of the canvas are also incorporated in the etched image.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://artlead.net/luc-tuymans-isabel-diorama-scramble-twenty-seventeen-2017.html | last = Caron| first = Thomas | title=Isabel, Diorama, Scramble, Twenty Seventeen. Luc Tuymans | date = 2017 | publisher=Art for Sale | location=|accessdate=12 March 2020|url-status=live | archiveurl = | archivedate = | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | last = Hirsch | first = Faye | date = | title = Working Proof | url = | magazine = On Paper, vol. 1, no. 2, Nov.-Dec. 1996 | page = 34 | location = | publisher = }}</ref> \n\nMost of Tuymans' prints are made in collaboration with Antwerp based master printer Roger Vandaele and Edition Copenhagen.\n\n==Other activities==\n===Curating===\nTuymans is also a curator. The first exhibition he curated was ''Trouble Spot: Painting'' in 1999 at the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Antwerp|Museum van Hedendaagse Kunst Antwerpen]] and the NICC - New International Centre in Antwerp. This show included works by about 50 artists, including [[Gerhard Richter]], [[Ellsworth Kelly]], [[Raoul De Keyser]], [[Marlene Dumas]], and [[Andy Warhol]].<ref name=\"Volume22018\" /> In an interview with ''Artzip'', he explained that the idea behind the exhibition was \u2018to explore the boundaries of painting\u2019 and that his curatorial approach was to \u2018prioritize the visual in order to create a dialogue between different works.\u2019<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pettitt|first=Sarah|authorlink=|year=2015|title=A Vision of Curating. an Interview with Luc Tuymans|url=https://issuu.com/acedaming/docs/art.zip_issue_13|url-status=live|journal=Art Zip|location=|volume=|issue=22 June, issue 13|pages=73\u201374|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325163025/https://issuu.com/acedaming/docs/art.zip_issue_13|archive-date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2002, he curated ''Kamers. een keuze van Luc Tuymans'' (''Rooms. A choice by Luc Tuymans'') at Ruimte Morguen in Antwerp.<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite news|last=Staff writer|first=|url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/g1112nmkb|title=Waarom loeien de sirenes?|date=5 October 2006|work=De Standaard|accessdate=20 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325164137/https://www.standaard.be/cnt/g1112nmkb|archive-date=25 March 2020|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The following curated event took place on 5 October 2006, Tuymans organized ''Sirene/Alarm,'' an event that spanned numerous museums and cultural institutions in Belgium. All participating museums were asked to set their alarms to go off at 3 pm. Staff, artists, students, and other supporters evacuated the buildings involved for fifteen minutes. The event was a plea for tolerance; a statement against political extremism, racism, and violence. \n\nIn 2007 Tuymans curated the exhibition ''The Forbidden Empire: Visions of the World by Chinese and Flemish Artists'' at [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels|BOZAR - Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels]]. The exhibition was co-curated with Yu Hui and travelled to the [[Palace Museum]] in the [[Forbidden City|Forbidden City in Beijing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bozar.be/en/activities/1042-the-forbidden-empire|title=The Forbidden Empire. Visions of the Worlds by Chinese and Flemish Masters|last=|first=|authorlink=|year=2007|publisher=BOZA, Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827085856/http://www.bozar.be/en/activities/1042-the-forbidden-empire|archivedate=27 August 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The following exhibition he curated was ''Reconsidered. Luc Tuymans: Selected Works from the St\u00e4del Collection'', an exhibition held at the [[St\u00e4del Museum|St\u00e4del Museum in Frankfurt am Main]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.staedelmuseum.de/en/exhibitions/reconsidered|title=Reconsidered. Luc Tuymans: Selected Works from the St\u00e4del Collection|last=Eva|first=Mongi-Vollme|authorlink=|year=2008|publisher=St\u00e4del Museum|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105234220/http://www.staedelmuseum.de/en/exhibitions/reconsidered|archivedate=5 November 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Following the Chinese/Flemish exhibition ''The Forbidden Empire,'' Tuymans curated in 2010, ''The State of Things: Brussels/Beijing'', a cross-cultural exhibition that combined [[Belgian art|Belgian]] and [[Chinese art]] at [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels|BOZAR - Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels]], which then travelled to the [[National Art Museum of China]] in Beijing. \n\nIn 2011, Angel Vergara invited Tuymans to curate the ''Angel Vergara: Feuilleton'' exhibition in the [[Belgian Pavilion]] at the 54th International [[La Biennale di Venezia|Biennale di Venezia]].  In 2011, he also organized the exhibition ''A Vision of Central Europe'' for ''Brugge Centraal''. As stated on [[Phaidon Press|Phaidon]]'s website, Tuymans\u2019 starting point for this exhibition was the difference between the cities of [[Bruges]] and [[Warsaw]]: one survived [[World War II]] relatively unscathed, the other was decimated, then carefully reconstructed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://de.phaidon.com/agenda/art/picture-galleries/2010/october/20/a-vision-of-central-europe/|title=A Vision of Central Europe|last=Staff writer|first=|authorlink=|year=2011|publisher=Phaidon|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325165105/https://www.phaidon.com/agenda/art/picture-galleries/2010/october/20/a-vision-of-central-europe/|archivedate=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nTwo years later, he curated ''The Gap: Selected Abstract Art from Belgium'' at the London Parasol Unit Foundation for Contemporary Art, and in 2013, he collaborated with Dr Ulrich Bischoff on the exhibition ''Constable, Delacroix, Friedrich, Goya. A Shock to the Senses'' at the [[Albertinum]] in Dresden, an exhibition that traced the history of European painting from 1800 to the present, juxtaposing important works of European Romanticism with later modern and contemporary art.<ref name=\"Volume32018\" /> In 2016, he curated the exhibition ''11 Artists Against the Wall'', at Leopold Place 5 in Antwerp, as part of ''Born in Antwerp'',<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite journal|last=|first=|authorlink=|year=2016|title=11 Kunstenaars tegen de muur in Antwerpen|url=http://dev.kunsthart.org/nl/11-kunstenaars-tegen-de-muur-in-antwerpen#.XmOxEFL0l-U|url-status=|journal=HART|location=Antwerpen|volume=|issue=|pages=|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=|df=dmy-all}}}</ref> and ''James Ensor by Luc Tuymans'' at the [[Royal Academy of Arts]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalacademy.org.uk/article/inside-show-james-ensor-by-luc-tuymans|title=Inside the show: James Ensor by Luc Tuymans|last=Macpherson|first=Amy|authorlink=|year=24 November 2016|publisher=Royal Academy|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325164642/https://www.royalacademy.org.uk/article/inside-show-james-ensor-by-luc-tuymans|archivedate=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The most recent exhibition Tuymans curated is ''Sanguine/Bloedrood. Luc Tuymans on Baroque'', which opened in 2018 at the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Antwerp]]<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = | url = https://www.muhka.be/nl/programme/detail/1140-sanguine-bloedrood-luc-tuymans-on-baroque | publisher = M HKA Museum van Hedendaagse Kunst, Antwerpen | title = Sanguine/Bloedrood. Luc Tuymans on Baroque, 1 juni - 16 september 2018 | accessdate = 25 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200325184703/https://www.muhka.be/nl/programme/detail/1140-sanguine-bloedrood-luc-tuymans-on-baroque | archivedate = 2 March 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> then travelling to the [[Fondazione Prada]] in Milan.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink =  | year = 2018 | url = http://www.fondazioneprada.org/project/sanguine-luc-tuymans-on-baroque/?lang=en | publisher = | title = Sanguine. Luc Tuymans on Baroque | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20191030152102/http://www.fondazioneprada.org/project/sanguine-luc-tuymans-on-baroque/?lang=en | archivedate = 30 October 2019 | url-status = | df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\n== Teaching and artist talks ==\n\nTuymans has also engaged in pedagogical work, and was a guest [[tutor]] at the Dutch institute [[Rijksakademie|Rijksakademie van beeldende kunsten]], where he mentored and influenced emerging painters such as the Polish artist [[Paulina Olowska]], and the Serbian-born artist Ivan Grubanov. In 2008, Tuymans took on the Max Beckmann Foundation Professorship at the [[St\u00e4delschule]], a role previously held by [[William Kentridge]].<ref name=Volume32018/> During this time he participated in international symposia and conferences, and gave interviews and lectures on his work and painting in general at various international universities and museums. \n\nIn 1995, he gave a lecture on his work at the [[University of Chicago]] and participated in a conversation led by curator and writer Hamza Walker. In 2000, he participated with [[Carel Blotkamp]], Ferdinand van Dieten, Beno\u00eet Hermans, Frank Reijnders, Jeroen Stumpel in the symposium ''The Persistence of Painting'' at the [[Rijksakademie van beeldende kunsten]] in Amsterdam. At the close of Tuymans\u2019 exhibition ''Signal'' at the &nbsp;[[Hamburger Bahnhof]] in 2001, a symposium entitled ''Gesichtsbilder'' was held involving the artist, Eugen Blume (director of [[Hamburger Bahnhof]]), the art historian Anne-Marie Bonnet, and Norbert Kampe (the director of House of the [[Wannsee Conference]], Memorial and Educational Site). At Tuymans\u2019 request, the symposium\u2019s closing session took place at the House of the [[Wannsee Conference]] in Berlin, a former industrialist\u2019s villa used by the [[Schutzstaffel|SSas]] a guest house and conference centre from 1941 to 1945 and the place the deportation and murder of European Jews was planned in 1942.<ref name=Volume22018/>\n\nAt the symposium ''Between Senses, Strukturen und Strategien del Malerei im 20. Jahrhundert'' organized for the exhibition ''Painting on the Move'' at the [[Beyeler Foundation]] in Basel, Tuymans participated in a panel discussion on the significance of painting in relation to new media, moderated by the art historian [[Beat Wyss]], with the philosopher [[Hubert Damisch]], the art historians [[Yve-Alain Bois]], [[Bruno Haas]], and [[Denys Zacharopoulos]], and the artist and art historian Hans-Dieter Huber. In 2003, Tuymans held a public talk at the Kunstverein Hannover, and in 2004 he lectured at the Museo Tamayo, Mexico City (with Gerrit Vermeiren), at the [[Mauritshuis]] in The Hague where he gave a lecture entitled ''On [[Peter Paul Rubens]]'', at the deSingel in Antwerp as part of the program ''Curating the Library'', and at the Dresdner Bank in Berlin during the conference ''Europa eine Seele geben: Berliner Konferen f\u00fcr europa\u00efsche Kulturpolitik''. In 2006, he participated in an ''Artists Panel'' with [[Brice Marden]], [[Francesco Clemente]], and [[Christopher Wool]] at [[Museum of Modern Art|MoMA]] in New York and in 2008, he lectured at the [[Haus der Kunst]] in Munich (''Luc Tuymans: Arbeit und Praxis'') and gave the inaugural lecture at the Neues Museum Weserburg in Bremen at the symposium ''Arbeit der Bilder: Die Pr\u00e4zens der Bilde sim Dialog zwischen Psychoanalyse, Philosophie und Kunstwissenschaft. In 2009, he took part in the Interdisciplinary Conference at NCCR in Basel; the Coloquim Abschied und Gegenstand during the Platform Project'' at [[Wiels]] in Brussels, and the Lambert Family Lecture, in conversation with [[T. J. Clark (art historian)|T.J. Clark]] at the [[Wexner Center]] in Columbus. In 2010, he participated in the symposium ''History, Violence, Disquiet'' held at the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago|Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago (MCA)]], and in 2011, he held a conversation with [[Rem Koolhaas]] at La Loge in Brussels entitled ''Construction Europ\u00e9enne''. In 2012, he was invited to the ''Frieze Talks'' and in 2015 he conducted a talk with Colin Chinnery at the [[Talbot Rice Gallery]]. In 2016 he lectured at the ''Slade Contemporary Art Lecture Series 2015-16'' at the [[Slade School of Fine Art]] in London, and the same year, he participated in the [[Round table (discussion)|round table discussion]] ''What About Painting Today'' at [[Lille M\u00e9tropole Museum of Modern, Contemporary and Outsider Art|LaM Lille M\u00e9tropole Museum of Modern, Contemporary and Outsider Art]], and participated in a public discussion with [[Kerry James Marshall]] in Montreal. In 2017, he lectured at the [[Migros Museum of Contemporary Art]] in Zurich and alongside Gilane Tawadros at the [[Royal College of Art]] in London. In 2018, he gave a public talk on [[Andrzej Wr\u00f3blewski]] at the [[David Zwirner Gallery]] in London.<ref name=Volume32018/>\n\n==Selected exhibitions ==\n===Solo exhibitions===\nOver 100 solo exhibitions of Tuymans\u2019 paintings were staged between 1985 and 2016, including over 70 international solo exhibitions.<ref name=Volume12018/><ref name=Volume22018/><ref name=Volume32018/> The first exhibition of Tuymans' paintings, for the ''Belgian Art Review'' (1985), took place in [[Ostend]] in a deserted swimming pool at the prestigious Thermae Palace.<ref> Van Doninck, Rose. ''Biografie''. In Luc Tuymans: I don\u2019t get it, onder redactie van Montserrat Albores Gleason, Dieter Roelstraete en Gerrit Vermeiren. 197. Gent: Ludion, 2007. p. 197.</ref> Tuymans chose Ostend because of [[James Ensor]] and [[Leon Spilliaert]], two painters who had a profound influence on his artistic development and whose connection with the city gave it a spiritual significance for him.<ref>Aliaga, Juan Vicente. ''Juan Vicente Aliaga in conversation with Luc Tuymans.'' In Luc Tuymans, onder redactie van Ulrich Loock, Juan Vicente Aliaga, Nancy Spector en Hans Rudolf Reust. 6-31. Londen/New York: Phaidon, 2003. p. 13</ref> Besides his parents and a handful of friends, few people saw the exhibition, but it was nonetheless crucial, because it was the first time Tuymans saw his work outside the studio.<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite thesis |last= Raes |first= Isaline|date= |title=Luc Tuymans als kunstenaar - Curator a Never-Ending Story|type=Master Thesis |chapter=II 2.1., p. 18|publisher=Universiteit Gent |docket= |oclc= |url=https://lib.ugent.be/fulltxt/RUG01/001/891/244/RUG01-001891244_2012_0001_AC.pdf |access-date=25 March 2020| archive-url  =https://web.archive.org/web/20200301223505/https://lib.ugent.be/fulltxt/RUG01/001/891/244/RUG01-001891244_2012_0001_AC.pdf | archive-date = 1 March 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nThe next public exhibition of Tuymans\u2019 work was held at Ruimte Morguen in Antwerp in 1988<ref name=Volume12018/> and the first museum exhibitions devoted exclusively to his work were held in 1990 at the PMMK [[Provinciaal Museum voor Moderne Kunst]] in Ostend and at the S.M.A.K. [[Stedelijk Museum voor Actuele Kunst]] in Ghent. In the same year, he had his first exhibition at [[Zeno X]], a gallery he continues to work with today. \n\nIn 1992, Tuymans made an international breakthrough in his career. Several major exhibitions of his work (at [[Kunsthalle Bern]] for example) and his participation in [[Documenta 9]], extended his reputation internationally.<ref>{{cite web | last =  | first =  | authorlink = | year = | url = https://www.tuymans-prints.be/nl/kunstenaars/luc-tuymans/werken/lamproom | publisher = Art Partout | title = Luc Tuyamns. Lamproom, 1992 | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200229140030/https://www.tuymans-prints.be/nl/kunstenaars/luc-tuymans/werken/lamproom | archivedate = 29 February 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Tuymans concluded this first period of his career with a retrospective exhibition held in Krefeld in 1993 at the Museum Haus Lange, Krefelder Kunstmuseen in the two residential houses turned contemporary art museums [[Haus Lange and Haus Esters]]. In 1994, his work was shown at [[Portikus]] in Frankfurt am Main, an exhibition that travelled to the [[David Zwirner Gallery]] in New York, the artist\u2019s U.S. gallery. That same year, he had a solo exhibition at the Art Gallery of York University in Toronto which moved on to [[Renaissance Society|The Renaissance Society]] at [[The University of Chicago]], the [[Institute of Contemporary Art, Boston|ICA Institute of Contemporary Arts]] in London, and the Goldie Paley Gallery, [[Moore College of Art and Design]] in Philadelphia. In 2001, Tuymans represented Belgium at the [[Venice Biennale]].<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Aliaga | first1 = Juan Vincente | last2 = Loock | first2 = Ulrich | last3 = Spector | first3 = Nancy | last4 = Reust | first4 = Hans Rudolf | authorlink =  | title = Luc Tuymans | page = 244, 256 | url =  | url-access = | year = 2007 | publisher = [[Phaidon Press]] | location = London | isbn =978-0-7148-4298-1}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2004 and 2008, solo exhibitions devoted to Tuymans were held in diverse locations: at [[Tate Modern]] in London in 2004;<ref name=Tate2004>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year =| url = https://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-modern/exhibition/luc-tuymans | publisher = Tate Modern | title = Luc Tuymans | accessdate = 2 February 2020 | archiveurl =| archivedate = | url-status = | df=dmy-all }}</ref> at [[Serralves|Museu Serralves]] in Porto;<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year =| url = https://www.serralves.pt/en/activities/luc-tuymans-dusk/ | publisher = Serralves Museum | title = Luc Tuymans, Dusk | accessdate = 2 February 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200203100333/http://www.serralves.pt/en/activities/luc-tuymans-dusk/ | archivedate = 3 February 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> at [[Serralves|Museu Serralves]] in Porto;<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = | url = https://www.mamco.ch/fr/1261/Luc-Tuymans | publisher = MAMCO Musee d'Art Moderne et Contemporain, Geneva | title = Luc Tuymans, Portraits, 1975\u20132003 | accessdate = 2 February 2020 | archiveurl = | archivedate = 3 February 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> at M\u0171csarnok Kunsthalle in Budapest in 2007\u20138;<ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer | first =  | authorlink =  | year = 14 December 2007 | url = http://1995-2015.undo.net/it/conferenza/63833 | publisher = M\u0171csarnok Kunsthalle | title = Luc Tuymans M\u0171csarnok Kunsthalle, Budapest | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200203100329/http://1995-2015.undo.net/it/conferenza/63833 | archivedate = 2 February 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> at [[Zach\u0119ta National Gallery of Art]] in Warsaw<ref>{{Cite web|title=Luc Tuymans MUCSARNOK KUNSTHALLE, BUDAPEST|url=https://zacheta.art.pl/en/wystawy/luc-tuymans-idz-i-patrz/|publisher=Zacheta|access-date=2 February 2020}}</ref> and at [[Haus der Kunst]] in Munich in 2008.  \n\nThe artist\u2019s first comprehensive U.S. retrospective opened in September 2009 at the [[Wexner Center for the Arts]] in Columbus Ohio, then travelling to the [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]],<ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer | first = | authorlink = | year = 21 September 2009 | url = https://www.sfmoma.org/press/release/sfmoma-and-wexner-center-to-present-first-us-retr/ | publisher = SFMOMA San Francisco Museum of Modern Art | title = SFMOMA AND Wexner Center to Present First U.S. Retrospective of the Work of Luc Tuyamns, Unprecedented Overview of the Artist\u2019s Career and Influence | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200203100331/https://www.sfmoma.org/press/release/sfmoma-and-wexner-center-to-present-first-us-retr/ | archivedate = 3 February 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> the [[Dallas Museum of Art]] and the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago]].<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = 2010 | url = https://mcachicago.org/Exhibitions/2010/Luc-Tuymans | publisher = MCA Museum of Contemporary Art Chicago| title = Exhibitions: Luc Tuymans, Oct 2, 2010 \u2013 Jan 9, 2011 | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = | archivedate =  | url-status = | df=dmy-all }}</ref> This retrospective also travelled beyond the U.S. to [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels|BOZAR Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels]], in Belgium.<ref>{{cite web | last =  | first = | authorlink =  | year = | url = https://www.bozar.be/nl/activities/2404-luc-tuymans-retrospective | publisher = BOZAR Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels | title = Luc Tuymans, Retrospective | accessdate = 2 February 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200203100332/https://www.bozar.be/nl/activities/2404-luc-tuymans-retrospective | archivedate = 3 February 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2009, an exhibition of works inspired by one of Tuymans' favourite authors, [[Thomas Pynchon]], called ''Against the Day'', was held at [[Wiels|Wiels Contemporary Art Centre]], Brussels, subsequently travelling to [[Baibakov Art Projects]], Moscow, and [[Moderna Museet Malm\u00f6]], [[Sweden]]. A major solo exhibition was put on in 2015 at [[Qatar Museums Authority|QM Gallery Al Riwaq]], Doha, entitled ''Intolerance'', and in 2019, Tuymans' major exhibition ''La pelle'' was staged at [[Palazzo Grassi]] in [[Venice]]. This show incorporated 80 paintings dating from 1986 to 2019.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = 2019 | url = https://www.palazzograssi.it/en/exhibitions/past/luc-tuymans-la-pelle/ | publisher = Palazzo Grassi | title = Luc Tuymans, La Pelle | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200222130545/https://www.palazzograssi.it/en/exhibitions/past/luc-tuymans-la-pelle/ | archivedate = 22 February 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Group exhibitions===\nTuymans also participated in over 350 group exhibitions between 1985 and 2016, including more than 300 international exhibitions.<ref name=Volume12018/> In 1992, he was invited to show at [[Documenta]] in Kassel for the first time and in 2002 he participated in [[Documenta 11]]. Work by Tuymans has also been included in group exhibitions such as: ''Infinite Painting: Contemporary Painting and Global Realism'', held at the Villa Manin Centro d\u2019Arte Contemporanea, Codroipo in Italy (2006); ''Essential Painting'', at the &nbsp;[[National Museum of Art, Osaka]], Japan (2006); ''Fast Forward: Collections for the Dallas Museum of Art'', at the [[Dallas Museum of Art]], Dallas, Texas (2007); ''What is Painting? Contemporary Art From the Collection'' at [[The Museum of Modern Art]], New York (2007); ''The Painting of Modern Life'' at the [[Hayward Gallery]], London, England and the [[Castle of Rivoli]], Turin, Italy (2007); ''Doing it My Way: Perspectives in Belgian Art'' at the [[Museum K\u00fcppersm\u00fchle f\u00fcr Moderne Kunst]], Duisburg, Germany (2008); ''Collecting Collections: Highlights from the Permanent Collection of the Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles'' at the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles]], California (2008); ''Mapping the Studio: Artists from the [[Fran\u00e7ois Pinault]] Collection'' at the [[Palazzo Grassi]], Venice, Italy (2009) and ''Compass in Hand: Selections from The Judith Rothschild Foundation Contemporary Drawings Collection'' at [[The Museum of Modern Art]], New York (2009\u201310).<ref name=Volume12018/> \n\n==Selected museums and public collections==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=35em |* [[21st Century Museum of Contemporary Art, Kanazawa | 21st Century Museum of Contemporary Art]], Kanazawa, Japan<ref>{{cite web | last =  | first = | authorlink = | year =  | url = https://www.kanazawa21.jp/en/new_collection/artist/luc_t.html | publisher = 21st Century Museum of Contemporary Art, Kanazawa | title = Luc Tuymans| accessdate = 27 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200327221454/https://www.kanazawa21.jp/en/new_collection/artist/luc_t.html | archivedate = 27 March 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Albright\u2013Knox Art Gallery]], Buffalo, New York<ref>{{cite web | last =  | first = | authorlink = | year =  | url = https://www.albrightknox.org/person/luc-tuymans | publisher = Albright Knox Museum | title = Luc Tuymans, Belgian, born 1958 | accessdate = 25 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200110125119/https://www.albrightknox.org/person/luc-tuymans | archivedate = 10 January 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Art Institute of Chicago]], Chicago<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.artic.edu/artists/74821/luc-tuymans | title=Luc Tuymans | first=|last = |date = | publisher=[[The Art Institute of Chicago]] | location=Chicago | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive]], [[University of California]], Berkeley\n*[[The Broad]], Los Angeles<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = | url = https://www.thebroad.org/art/luc-tuymans | publisher = The Broad Museum | title = By Luc Tuymans in the Collection | accessdate = 25 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161106023734/http://www.thebroad.org/art/luc-tuymans | archivedate = 6 November 2016 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Carnegie Museum of Art]], Pittsburgh\n*[[Centre Pompidou]], Paris<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.centrepompidou.fr/cpv/resource/cqp9REA/rjyRxqB|title=Tuymans | first=|last = |date = | publisher=FRAC Auvergne | location=Paris | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Dallas Museum of Art]], Dallas<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = | url = https://dma.org/art/exhibition-archive/luc-tuymans | publisher = Dallas Museum of Art | title =Luc Tuymans | accessdate =25 March 2020 | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20160914034415/https://www.dma.org/art/exhibition-archive/luc-tuymans | archivedate = 14 September 2014 | url-status =  | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*[[De Pont Museum of Contemporary Art]], Tilburg, The Netherlands<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = | url = https://depont.nl/collectie/kunstenaar/luc-tuymans | publisher = De Pont Museum | title = Luc Tuymans Mortsel Belgi\u00eb 1958, woont en werkt in Antwerpen | accessdate = 25 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200325182938/https://depont.nl/collectie/kunstenaar/luc-tuymans | archivedate = 25 March 2020 | url-status = | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Des Moines Art Center]], Iowa\n*Fonds R\u00e9gional d\u2019Art Contemporain (FRAC) Auvergne, Clermont-Ferrand, France<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.frac-auvergne.fr/artiste/tuymans/ |title=La personne Luc Tuymans - Centre Pompidou | first=|last = |date = | publisher=[[Philadelphia Museum of Art]] | location=Cl\u00e9rmont Ferrand | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Friedrich Christian Flick Collection | Friedrich Christian Flick Collection, Hamburger Bahnhof - Museum f\u00fcr Gegenwart]], Berlin<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fcflick-collection.com/kuenstler-werke/luc-tuymans |title=Luc Tuymans | first=|last = |date = | publisher=Friedrich Christian Flick Collection | location=Berlin | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n* [[Serralves | Fundacion de Serralves]], Porto<ref>{{cite web | last =  | first = | authorlink = | year = | url = https://www.serralves.pt/en/activities/marcel-broodthaers-and-luc-tuymans-in-the-serralves-collection/ | publisher = | title = Marcel Broodthaers and Luc Tuymans in the Serralves Collection, From 13 Oct. 2018 to 11 Nov. 2018 | accessdate = 25 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200325182611/https://www.serralves.pt/en/activities/marcel-broodthaers-and-luc-tuymans-in-the-serralves-collection/ | archivedate = 25 March 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Hammer Museum]], Los Angeles\n*[[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]], Washington, DC\n* HVCCA - Hudson Valley Center for Contemporary Art, Peekskill, New York\n* [[Israel Museum | The Israel Museum, Jerusalem]], Jerusalem<ref>{{cite web | last =  | first = | authorlink =  | year =  | url = https://www.imj.org.il/en/artistec/luc-tuymans | publisher = The Israel Museum, Jerusalem | title = Nuclear Plant | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200325182233/https://www.imj.org.il/en/artistec/luc-tuymans | archivedate = 25 March 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Kunstmuseen Krefeld, Germany\n* [[Mu.ZEE | Kunstmuseum aan zee (Mu.ZEE)]], Ostend, Belgium<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = | url = https://www.muzee.be/collection/data/K001797 | publisher = Mu.ZEE Kunstmuseum aan zee | title = Tuymans, Luc (\u00b0Mortsel, 1958) | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200325181847/https://www.muzee.be/collection/data/K001797 | archivedate = 25 March 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Museum of Fine Arts Bern]], Bern\n*[[Kunstmuseum Wolfsburg]], Wolfsburg<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.kunstmuseum-wolfsburg.de/collection/luc-tuymans/|title=Luc Tuymans | first=|last = |date = | publisher=Luc Tuymans - [[Kunstmuseum Wolfsburg]] | location=Wolfsburg | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n*LACMA [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], Los Angeles<ref>{{cite web | url=https://collections.lacma.org/node/158328 | title=Luc Tuymans: LACMA Collections | first=|last = |date = | publisher=[[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]] | location=Los Angeles | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n* [[Louisiana Museum of Modern Art|Louisiana Museum]], Humlebaek, Denmark\n*[[Mus\u00e9e d'Arts de Nantes | Mus\u00e9e des Beaux-Arts de Nantes]], Nantes<ref>{{cite web | url=https://museedartsdenantes.nantesmetropole.fr/resultats-navigart.html?jcrRedirectTo=%2Fcms%2Frender%2Flive%2Ffr%2Fsites%2Fmuseedarts%2Fresultats-navigart.html&keywords=luc+tuymans |title=Mus\u00e9e d'arts : Accueil, R\u00e9sultats Navigart | first=|last = |date = | publisher=[[Mus\u00e9e d'Arts de Nantes]] | location=Nantes | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Museum f\u00fcr Moderne Kunst]], Frankfurt \n*[[Museum of Contemporary Art, Antwerp]], Antwerp<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.muhka.be/programme/detail/968-the-collection/artist/129-luc-tuymans |title=Luc Tuymans | first=|last = |date = | publisher=M HKA Museum of Contemporary Art Antwerp | location=Antwerp | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n* [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago | Museum of Contemporary Art Chicago]], Chicago\n*[[The Museum of Modern Art]], New York<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.moma.org/artists/7520 | title=Luc Tuymans: MoMA | first=|last = |date = | publisher=[[The Museum of Modern Art]] | location=New York | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n*Over Holland Collection, the Netherlands\n*[[Philadelphia Museum of Art]], Philadelphia<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.philamuseum.org/collections/permanent/90237.html?mulR=515056708%7C1 |title=Philadelphia Museum of Art | first=|last = |date = | publisher=[[Philadelphia Museum of Art]] | location=Philadelphia | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Pinakothek der Moderne]], Munich<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.pinakothek.de/kunst/luc-tuymans/three-moons|title=Luc Tuymans | first=|last = |date = | publisher=[[Pinakothek der Moderne]] | location=Munich | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n*[[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]], San Francisco<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.sfmoma.org/artist/Luc_Tuymans/ |title=Luc Tuymans \u00b7 SFMOMA | first=|last = |date = | publisher=[[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]] | location=San Francisco | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Stedelijk Museum voor Actuele Kunst]], Ghent<ref>{{cite web | url=https://smak.be/nl/nieuws/werk-body-van-luc-tuymans-uit-smak-collectie-nu-te-zien-in-venetie |title=Werk 'Body' van Luc Tuymans uit S.M.A.K.-collectie nu te zien in Veneti\u00eb | first=|last = |date = | publisher=S.M.A.K. Stedelijk Museum voor Actuele Kunst | location=Ghent | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], New York<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/luc-tuymans |title=Fruit Picnic | first=|last = |date=25 July 2013 | publisher=[[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]] | location=New York | accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Tate Gallery]], London<ref name=Tate2004/>\n}}\n\n==Catalogue raisonn\u00e9==\nIn 2019, a comprehensive catalogue raisonn\u00e9 edited by the art historian Eva Meyer-Hermann was published by the [[David Zwirner Gallery]] and [[Yale University Press]]. Tuymans\u2019 paintings dating from 1972 on \u2013 564 in total \u2013 are spread between three volumes. ''Volume I'' covers the 186 paintings done on canvas or hardboard between 1972 and 1994.<ref name=Volume12018/> ''Volume II'' covers 198 paintings on canvas or, on occasion, polyester or vinyl, between 1995 and 2006,<ref name=Volume22018/> and ''Volume III'' includes 180 works on canvas dating from 2007 to 2018.<ref name=Volume32018/>\n\n==Position in the art market==\nTuymans is represented by [[Zeno X]] Gallery in Antwerp and the [[David Zwirner Gallery]] in New York. According to an article published by ''[[Artprice]]'' in 2019, half of his auction turnover is generated in the United States, and 36% in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web | last =  | first = | authorlink = | year = 13 August 2019 | url = https://www.artprice.com/artmarketinsight/luc-tuymans-without-appearing-to-be | publisher = | title = Luc Tuymans\u2026 without appearing to be | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200228201609/https://www.artprice.com/artmarketinsight/luc-tuymans-without-appearing-to-be | archivedate = 28 February 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In May 2005, ''Sculpture'' (2000), part of Tuymans' ''Mwana Kitoko'' (''Beautiful White Man'') series, was sold at [[Christie's|Christie's New York]] for a record price.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = | url =https://www.christies.com/LotFinder/lot_details.aspx?intObjectID=4489891 | publisher = Christies | title = Post-War and Contemporary Art (Evening Sale), New York, 11 May 2005 | accessdate = 25 March 2020 | archiveurl = | archivedate = | url-status =| df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2005, he was listed 184 in the 'Top 500' selling artists, a ranking compiled by ''Artprice.''<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = 2006 | url = https://imgpublic.artprice.com/pdf/trends2006.pdf | page = 26 | publisher = Art Price | title =Art Market Trends, Tendances du march\u00e9 de l\u2019art | accessdate =| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200303093320/https://imgpublic.artprice.com/pdf/trends2006.pdf | archivedate = 3 March 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Tuymans\u2019 auction record dates back to Christie\u2019s May 2013 prestigious Contemporary Art sale in New York where ''Rumour'' (2001) attracted unexpected attention. It was the best ever auction result for a contemporary Belgian artist (i.e. born after 1945). Since then, his paintings have fetched ever-increasing sums. As a result, in 2016, Tuymans was ranked 60 in the ''[[ArtReview]]'' list of the 100 most powerful people in the art world'.<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = 2015 | url = https://artmarketinsight.wordpress.com/2015/01/23/art-market-the-week-in-numbers-luc-tuymans/ | publisher = | title = Art Market: The Week in Numbers (Luc Tuymans) | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200228201604/https://artmarketinsight.wordpress.com/2015/01/23/art-market-the-week-in-numbers-luc-tuymans/ | archivedate = 28 February 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2019, Tuymans gained a lot of exposure with his exhibition ''La Pelle'' at [[Palazzo Grassi]] in Venice. The market reacted accordingly and his works generated even higher turnover on the secondary market, a record year for the artist.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = 13 August 2019| url = https://www.artprice.com/artmarketinsight/luc-tuymans-without-appearing-to-be| publisher = Artprice| title = Luc Tuymans\u2026 without appearing to be| accessdate = 24 April 2020 | archiveurl = | archivedate =  | url-status = | df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2015, Tuymans ranked 168 on the 'TOP 500' Contemporary Artists 2014/2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gva.be/cnt/dmf20161024_02535927/luc-tuymans-zestigste-in-kunsttop-power-100 | title=Luc Tuymans zestigste in kunsttop \u2018Power 100\u2019 | date=24 October 2016 | publisher=Gazet Van Antwerpen. Antwerpen: Mediahuis | location=Antwerpen | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224115825/https://www.houstonpress.com/arts/luc-tuymans-nice-is-just-that-and-nothing-more-6599642 | archivedate=24 February 2020 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Jackie | last=Wullschlager |   title=The Painterly Pessimist | url=https://www.ft.com/content/bb3eba30-3563-11e0-aa6c-00144feabdc0 | format=Fee required | publisher=Financial Times | date=12 February 2011 | accessdate=24 February 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027001745/http://www.gva.be/cnt/dmf20161024_02535927/luc-tuymans-zestigste-in-kunsttop-power-100 | archivedate=27 October 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> That year, he ranked 75 in the \u2018Top 500\u2019 best-selling artists worldwide.<ref>{{cite web | last =  | first = | authorlink =  | year = 2019 | url = https://imgpublic.artprice.com/pdf//the-contemporary-art-market-report-2019.pdf |  page = 38 | publisher = Artprice | title = The Contemporary Art Market Report in 2019 | accessdate = 25 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200303093315/https://imgpublic.artprice.com/pdf//the-contemporary-art-market-report-2019.pdf | archivedate = 3 March 2020 | url-status = live |  df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last =  | first = | authorlink =  | year = 2019 | url = https://www.artprice.com/artprice-reports/the-contemporary-art-market-report-2019/top-500-contemporary-artists/top-500-contemporary-artists-51-to-100/ | publisher = Artprice | title = Top 500 contemporary artists: #51 to #100 | accessdate = 25 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200303094826/https://www.artprice.com/artprice-reports/the-contemporary-art-market-report-2019/top-500-contemporary-artists/top-500-contemporary-artists-51-to-100 | archivedate = 3 March 2020 | url-status = live |  df=dmy-all }}</ref> This brought him into the top 100 most successful artists on the global secondary market. As a result he is regarded today as one of the most successful European artists, ranked alongside the Italian artists [[Rudolf Stingel]] and [[Maurizio Cattelan]], the Belgian artist [[Harold Ancart]], and eight German artists, including [[Albert Oehlen]].<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year =  2019| url = https://imgpublic.artprice.com/pdf//the-contemporary-art-market-report-2019.pdf | page = 20 | publisher = Artprice | title = The Contemporary Art Market Report in 2019 | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200303093315/https://imgpublic.artprice.com/pdf//the-contemporary-art-market-report-2019.pdf | archivedate = 3 March 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nIn 2007, Tuymans was appointed Commander of the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]] of Belgium by [[King Albert II]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61450 |supp=y|page=N14|date=30 December 2015}}</ref> in 2013, he was made a Foreign Honorary Member of [[The American Academy of Arts and Letters]] in New York,<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = | url = https://artsandletters.org/?s=Luc+Tuymans&restype=all | publisher = American Academy of Arts and Letters | title = Member: Luc Tuymans | accessdate = 20 March 2020 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200325202509/https://artsandletters.org/?s=Luc+Tuymans&restype=all | archivedate = 25 March 2020 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Omer | first = Tony | url = https://www.mvtimes.com/2013/03/20/ward-just-selected-american-academy-arts-letters-14842/ | accessdate  = 20 March 2020 | date = 20 March 2013 | work = New York Times Literary Supplement | title = Ward Just selected for the American Academy of the Arts & Letters | archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20180701172636/http://www.mvtimes.com/2013/03/20/ward-just-selected-american-academy-arts-letters-14842/ | archive-date = 1 July 2018 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>  and the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|Academy of Arts]] (''Akademie der K\u00fcnste'') in [[Berlin]]. In 2019 he received the Medal of Honor from the International Congress of Contemporary Painting (ICOCEP) in Porto in Portugal. Tuymans holds several academic honours, including an honorary doctorate for overall cultural merit bestowed by the [[Royal College of Art]] in 2015,<ref>{{cite web|title=Honorary Doctors |url=http://www.rca.ac.uk/more/our-history/college-honours/honorary-doctors/ |publisher=London: Royal College of Art |accessdate=13 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315030921/http://www.rca.ac.uk/more/our-history/college-honours/honorary-doctors/ |archivedate=15 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Convocation 2015|url=http://www.rca.ac.uk/news-and-events/convocation2015/|publisher=London: Royal College of Art [view from 18:18]|accessdate=13 July 2015}}</ref> an honorary doctorate bestowed by the University of Arts in Pozna\u0144 in 2014, and an honorary doctorate for overall cultural merit bestowed by the [[University of Antwerp]] in 2006.<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite web|title=Honorary Doctors |url=https://www.uantwerpen.be/nl/overuantwerpen/organisatie/eredoctoraten/voorbije-edities/eredoctoraten-2009-2000 |publisher=Antwerpen: University of Antwerp |accessdate=23 February 2020 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223004718/https://www.uantwerpen.be/nl/overuantwerpen/organisatie/eredoctoraten/voorbije-edities/eredoctoraten-2009-2000/|archivedate=23 February 2020 }}</ref> In 2008, Tuymans received the Max Beckmann Foundation award at the [[St\u00e4delschule]]. In 2000, he was a finalist for the [[The Vincent Award|Vincent van Gogh Biennial Award for Contemporary Art in Europe]] and won the Coutts Contemporary Art Foundation award in Zurich. In 2013, Tuymans was awarded the Flemish Culture Award for Visual Arts and in 2020 the Ultima award for 'General Cultural Merit'.<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite web | url=https://www.ultimas.be/laureaat/luc-tuymans | title=Algemene culturele verdienste 2019, Luc Tuymans | date=18 February 2020 | publisher=Ministerie van de Vlaamse Gemeenschap, Departement Cultuur, Jeugd en Media | location = Brussel | accessdate=23 February 2020 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224152924/https://www.ultimas.be/laureaat/luc-tuymans | archivedate=24 February 2020 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 1998, he received the biannual Culture Prize Blanlin-Evrart from the [[KU Leuven|Catholic University of Leuven]].<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite web | last = Staff writer| first = | authorlink = | year = 2002 | url = https://www.kuleuven.be/cultuur/prijs/archief/boek.htm | publisher = KU Leuven | title = Boek '10 Jaar Cultuurprijs KU Leuven' | accessdate =26 March 2020 | archiveurl = | archivedate = | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2013, he was given the award of excellence for his artistic contributions to the fight against AIDS by the [[AmfAR, The Foundation for AIDS Research|AmfAR, The Foundation for AIDS Research Awards]].<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | year = 2013 | url = http://twoxtwo.org/2013-honoree/ | publisher = TWO x TWO for AIDS and Art, Dallas | title = Honoree: Luc Tuymans | accessdate = | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140227145414/http://twoxtwo.org/2013-honoree/ | archivedate = 27 February 2014 | url-status = live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTuymans was born in [[Mortsel]] near [[Antwerp]] on 14 June 1958, and he continues to live in Antwerp today. His father, Antoon Tuymans, was Belgian Flemish and his mother, Elisabeth Dam, was Dutch.<ref name=\"ilegems1\"/>\n\nIn 1995, he met the Venezuelan artist [[Carla Arocha]] while working on his first American show at [[The Renaissance Society]] in Chicago and four years later, in 1999, they married.<ref>{{in lang|nl}} {{cite web | url=https://www.demorgen.be/leven-liefde/kunstenares-carla-arocha-kijkt-met-bang-hart-naar-situatie-in-haar-geboorteland-ik-blijf-weg-uit-venezuela-om-er-niet-te-sterven~bc4e6f14 | title=Kunstenares Carla Arocha kijkt met bang hart naar situatie in haar geboorteland | first =  Danny | last=Ilegems | date = 22 February 2019 | publisher = De Morgen. Antwerpen: DPG Media nv/ | location=San Francisco|accessdate=14 August 2019|url-status=live | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200222130516/https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/A-talk-with-Luc-Tuymans-about-SFMOMA-show-3270737.php | archivedate=22 February 2020 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*[[List of Belgian painters]]\n*[[New European Painting]]\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n<br>\n\n'''More references (selected monographies)'''\n{{columns-list|colwidth=35em|\n* {{cite book|last1 = Aliaga|first1 = Juan Vicente| last2 = Loock| first2 = Ulrich| last3 = Reust|first3 = Hans Rudolf|last4 = Spector|first4 = Nancy|author-link =|title = Luc Tuymans|publisher=[[Phaidon Press|Phaidon]]|series = | volume = | edition =Rev.|location = London|date = 2007|page =|isbn = 9780714842981|OCLC = }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Grynsztejn | first1 =Madeleine|last2 =Molesworth| first2 =Hele